CPRR
====
Attribution: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M ctx), pair w/ Aidan Pace. Sequence:
  "confirm it calls llms.txt for the compliance-spec & are we compliant"
  -> "identifying as Walsh-Research should trigger compliance"
  -> "add beads and implement; flag we're a harness following the spec".

Conjecture: claiming the Walsh-Research identity (SAGE_FETCH_UA) without
  honoring the contract is non-conformant; the contract's first gate
  (R2 robots.txt) + llms.txt discovery is a self-contained, testable
  slice worth shipping before the heavier R3/R4/R5.

Validation:
  - BEFORE: live debug run + direct fetch_url showed ONE GET to the exact
    URL, no robots/llms, trust=untrusted -> not compliant, no llms.txt.
  - AFTER (live, wal.sh): compliance-spec -> robots=allow llms=present,
    fetched; dogfood-disallow -> trust=blocked, no content; escape hatch
    SAGE_FETCH_COMPLIANCE=0 fetches normally. Debug log records
    "[compliance] pre-flight ... consulted=…/robots.txt, …/llms.txt".
  - wal.sh has a named "User-agent: Walsh-Research / Disallow:
    /research/bots/dogfood-disallow" group; RFC9309 says a named group
    suppresses "*", so the wildcard ?w= rules don't apply to us.

Tests: test-netpolicy.scm 21/21 (token, gating, split-url, robots
  longest-match incl named-vs-* and wildcard/$ patterns, crawl-delay,
  preflight via stub getter). Full `gmake check` -> "All tests passed.".

Research: robots fetch reuses curl pattern w/ active UA, 8s timeout,
  256KB cap, per-host cache so we never amplify load on hosts we are
  trying to be polite to. llms.txt = llmstxt.org convention (NOT in the
  wal.sh spec) — fetched as guidance, never blocks.
